threat_severity.level_description: Severity MEDIUM because it was considered trojan.

attributes.magic: ELF 32-bit MSB executable, MIPS, MIPS-I version 1 (SYSV), statically linked, stripped

crowdsourced_ai_results.analysis: This MIPS-based ELF binary is a multifunctional IoT botnet agent, likely a variant of the Mirai family. It exhibits standard worm-like propagation, persistence, and backdoor behaviors. Key malicious activities include: 1) Scanning random IP addresses and attempting to deploy payloads via command injection (wget/curl/tftp) for multiple architectures (mipsel, armv4l). 2) Establishing a persistent backdoor by listening on a network socket, providing a custom password-protected prompt, and spawning shell processes (/bin/bash, /bin/sh) upon 'Access granted'. 3) Anti-forensics and process management logic that iterates through /proc to identify and terminate system utilities (ps, netstat) and competing malware downloaders. 4) Hardware watchdog manipulation via /dev/watchdog to prevent system reboots during operation. Relevant IOCs include the C2 IP 89.116.20.194:81 and command templates used for downloading additional malicious components to /tmp or /dev/shm.
